nographic material drawn from years of fieldwork in Mexico with historical material from a variety of sources, Stephen shows how activists have appropriated symbols of the revolution to build the contemporary political movement. Her wide-ranging narrative touches on the history of land tenure, racism, gender issues in the Zapatista movement, local political culture, the Zapatista uprising of the 1990s and its aftermath, and more. A significant addition to our knowledge of social change in contemporary Mexico, Zapata Lives! also offers readers a model for engaged, activist anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndians of MexicoxSocial conditions. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozChiapasxGovernment relations. 0aSocial movementszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a2000.  aactivism.  aactivist.  aanthropologist.  acontemporary.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  acultural.  aeconomic policy.  aeconomics.  aelections.  aethnographic.  aethnography.  afieldwork.  agender issues.  agovernment.  ahuman rights.  ajuly 2020.  aland reform.  alatin america.  alegal issues.  alegal reform.  amexico.  amodern world.  aneoliberal.  aoaxaca.  apolitical culture.  apolitical.  apolitics.  aracism.  arebellion.  arural communities.  arural mexico.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  asocioeconomic.  asouth america.  asouthern mexico.  avicente fox.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022237340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092764340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520927643/original  a978-3-11-069042-2 